{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01RqJq4qg6Bko2yH2xsHRMcP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to analyze a set of behaviors for a REST API product search system and determine the minimum test infrastructure level needed to catch real failures for each behavior. Let me think through each behavior carefully using the level definitions and key questions provided.\n\nThe system has these components:\n1. REST API accepting natural language queries\n2. Embedding model converting queries to vectors\n3. Vector database with similarity search\n4. LLM re-ranking step\n\nThe levels are:\n- Unit: one local function, no I/O\n- Integration: several modules wired, local DB/filesystem\n- System: subprocess, OS, real HTTP, real external API\n- Agentic: depends on real LLM non-determinism or real AI/ML model\n- Workflow: multiple agentic steps in sequence or full agent pipeline\n\nLet me analyze each behavior:\n\n## Behavior 1: Embedding vector dimensionality\n\n\"The embedding vector produced for a given query string has the correct dimensionality for the vector database index.\"\n\nKey questions:\n- MOCK-MISS: Could a pure mock miss this? Yes - you could mock the embedding API to return any dimensionality, and if the code just validates the dimension without using it, the test passes. But the real embedding model produces vectors of a specific dimension.\n- REAL-INFRA: Does it depend on OS/network/subprocess? The embedding model call does - it's calling an external embedding service.\n- LLM-DEP: Does correctness depend on LLM non-determinism? Not really - the dimensionality is deterministic for a given embedding model. The embedding model produces consistent dimensionality.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Would mocking the embedding model hide a failure? YES - if you mock it to return dimension 768 but the real model returns 1536, a unit test with a mock would pass but production would fail.\n\nThis feels like it MUST be at least System or Agentic level because:\n\n\nYou need to call the REAL embedding model to verify it produces the correct dimensionality, since the embedding model is an external ML service. The dimensionality itself is deterministic for a given model and doesn't vary across runs, so while we need the real embedding model, the outcome is predictable. Let me reconsider whether this truly requires Agentic level or if System level suffices.\n\nThe definition states \"depends on real LLM non-determinism or a real AI/ML model call\" - calling a real AI/ML model could qualify as Agentic. However, the spirit seems to distinguish between tests that depend on non-deterministic variations versus those that just verify a deterministic property of an external service. The practical test here needs to confirm the embedding model produces vectors with the expected dimension and that the code correctly validates this, which is really about verifying a fixed characteristic of the service rather than handling unpredictable behavior.\n\nCalling the real embedding API would fall under System level since it's an external API call. Though embedding models are technically AI/ML systems, the dimensionality they produce is deterministic - the same model always returns the same vector size. So the minimum level required is System, not Agentic. could run a local vector database instance in tests, you'd verify the similarity ordering works. But if the real system uses a specific vector DB service with particular indexing or configuration, you might need System level to catch environment-specific issues.\n\nMinimum level: **Integration** (local vector DB instance)\n\nProbability distribution: Integration 0.70, System 0.25, Unit 0.05 (Unit only if you're testing the sorting logic in isolation, but that wouldn't verify actual similarity search behavior)\n\nFor the LLM re-ranking behavior, the key consideration is whether the LLM's reordering logic can be tested without calling an actual LLM. If you mock the LLM responses, you lose visibility into whether re-ranking actually changes the order based on nuanced query intent. You'd need either a real LLM or a deterministic mock with carefully crafted responses that demonstrate the re-ranking effect. This pushes toward System level if using a real LLM API, or Integration if you can mock LLM responses convincingly enough to show the reordering happens.\n\nHowever, since LLMs are non-deterministic by nature (unless temperature is set to 0), running the same test multiple times could yield different re-ranking orders. This variability means you're testing actual LLM behavior, not just the mechanics of the re-ranking pipeline. The test requires real embedding vectors, actual similarity search, and a real LLM call to verify the re-ranking produces different orderings for nuanced queries.\n\nThis is **Agentic** level - the behavior depends on non-deterministic LLM outputs that can't be reliably mocked or predicted.\n\nFor the next behavior about empty results, the core issue is whether the system properly filters out low-relevance matches from the vector database. Mocking the similarity search to return nothing would pass the test, but the real vector DB might return results with low similarity scores that need filtering. You need the actual vector database and its genuine similarity scores to catch whether the filtering logic works correctly.\n\nTesting this requires a real vector DB instance—either local or cloud—populated with vectors that are far from your test query. You'd run the similarity search and confirm the API correctly excludes low-similarity results. This is Integration level if you can use a local instance.\n\nFor latency testing, the question becomes whether you can measure actual end-to-end performance or if you need to mock the external services.\n\nMocking would mask real latency issues since actual embedding services, vector databases, and LLMs all have variable performance characteristics. Network delays, service response times, and model inference speed all contribute to the total latency. Testing with real infrastructure is necessary to capture these factors—embedding service latency, vector DB query time, LLM service latency, and your code's processing overhead all need to be measured together. If the 2-second median is an SLA requirement, you need real systems to validate it.\n\nThis falls into **System** level testing at minimum, possibly **Agentic** if you're measuring against actual LLM service calls. The latency itself is somewhat non-deterministic since it varies between runs, but the core requirement is testing with realistic latencies rather than instant mocks to catch actual performance failures.\n\nThe failure modes break down into three categories: unoptimized code (catchable at Integration level with local services), network delays (requires System level with real network calls), and slow LLM inference (requires Agentic level with actual service calls). To catch all of them, you'd need at least System level testing. Most issues would likely surface in an Integration test using a local vector database, but the complete picture demands real external service latencies.\n\nNow I need to structure the response properly. The user wants specific fields: behavior_id, description, minimum_level, justification, test_description, plan_consistent, and level_probabilities. For each behavior, I'm determining what infrastructure is truly necessary to expose real failures rather than just validating happy paths.\n\nStarting with embedding dimensionality: the code calls an embedding API, receives a vector, and checks its dimensions. A mocked embedding in a Unit test would pass trivially, but I need to consider what could actually fail in production.\n\nA real embedding service returning incorrect dimensions would only be caught by calling an actual embedding provider. Whether that's a local model running as a subprocess or a cloud API, it requires moving beyond Unit testing. If the embedding model runs locally as a deterministic service, Integration testing with that real model would suffice. However, cloud-based embedding APIs typically require System-level testing since they're external dependencies. The key distinction is whether the failure mode (wrong dimensionality from the actual embedding service) can be caught without hitting the real service—and it can't be, so minimum level depends on deployment architecture.\n\nFor vector similarity ordering, the vector database must return results in the correct order based on actual similarity calculations. Mocking the database won't reveal ordering failures. A local vector DB with real vectors would catch this at Integration level, while a cloud vector DB would require System testing.\n\nFor LLM re-ranking, the non-deterministic nature of the model means you need to call the actual LLM to verify it's changing the result order. The real risks aren't just that order changes—it's whether the LLM fails to rerank at all, produces worse rankings, or times out. These failure modes only surface when hitting the real model, making Agentic the minimum level.\n\nTo properly test this behavior, you'd need real embeddings with actual similarity semantics, real vector search returning cosine similarities, and the real LLM to validate its reranking effectiveness on nuanced queries. Mocking the LLM could test the integration plumbing, but wouldn't verify the actual reranking quality. The requirement fundamentally depends on real LLM behavior.\n\nBehavior 4 involves filtering search results below a similarity threshold. Testing requires vectors in the database that genuinely don't match the query, plus real vector search to produce actual similarity scores—this catches cases where the threshold is misconfigured or filtering logic fails. A local vector DB at the integration level would suffice since the threshold comparison itself is deterministic.\n\nBehavior 5 measures end-to-end latency including network calls. Catching slowness requires realistic network conditions and actual external service latencies, not just local execution.  LLM inference is the dominant latency factor, so system-level testing with real network/external services is the minimum, though agentic-level testing with actual LLM inference would be more comprehensive.\n\nNow I need to verify that each test description actually aligns with its minimum level requirement. For instance, if I claim a test needs system-level testing but the description only requires integration-level capabilities, that's inconsistent. Let me check: embedding dimensionality should call a real embedding API, similarity ordering needs an actual vector database, LLM reranking requires real model inference, empty results handling needs vector DB interaction, and latency measurement demands realistic external service calls. I'll make sure each test description matches what I've identified as necessary.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13315,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13315},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"90f8d13b-3e5b-4717-8fe3-7cca22d29701","uuid":"efebb260-bb58-4f7e-9a30-9144bdb32f10"}
